**Mifune Shrine** (みふねじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Sessha|Q1071160|qid=Q1071160|lt=subsidiary shrine|1=Setsumatsusha}} of the {{ill|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|Q687168|qid=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} {{ill|lt=Kōtaijingū|Q11581011|qid=Q11581011|1=Kōtai Jingū}} (Inner Shrine). This article also describes **Mumino Shrine** (むみのじんじゃ), which is enshrined at the same site as Mifune Shrine.

Both are shrines that enshrine {{ill|lt=water deities|Q3137449|qid=Q3137449|lt=river gods|1=Suijin}}.<ref name="ic">Ise Bunkasha, ed. (2008): p. 64</ref>

=== Overview ===
This section describes matters common to both shrines.

They are located in Toba (pronounced *Toba* or *Doba*), {{ill|lt=Taki Town|Q1203963|qid=Q1203963|1=Taki, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Taki District|Q1042360|qid=Q1042360|1=Taki District, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Mie Prefecture|Q128196|qid=Q128196|1=Mie Prefecture}}.<ref name="sk8">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p. 378</ref> The local {{ill|lt=place name|Q7884789|qid=Q7884789|1=Toponym}} “Toba” means “stopping place,” and is said to derive from the tradition that the boat of {{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-Mikoto|Q4388732|qid=Q4388732|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}} once stopped there.<ref name="tc5">Kaneko (1983): p. 55</ref>

The {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine buildings|1=UNKNOWN}} are constructed in the {{ill|lt=Shinmei-zukuri|Q930545|qid=Q930545|1=Shinmei-zukuri}} style and are surrounded by a {{ill|lt=tamagaki|Q3078312|qid=Q3078312|1=Sacred fences}} fence. There is no {{ill|lt=offering box|Q988479|qid=Q988479|1=Saisen}}. A {{ill|lt=stone lantern|Q762277|qid=Q762277|1=Nightlight}} stands at the entrance to the shrine grounds.<ref name="ic"/> The total {{ill|lt=area|Q11500|qid=Q11500|1=Area}} of the grounds is 975 {{ill|lt=tsubo|Q706688|qid=Q706688|1=Pyeong}} (approximately 3,223 {{ill|lt=square meters|Q25343|qid=Q25343|lt=m<sup>2</sup>|1=Square metre}}).<ref name="sk0">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p. 380</ref>

=== Mifune Shrine ===
Mifune Shrine ranks 24th among the 27 subsidiary shrines of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Hall, ed. (1929): pp. 9–11</ref> It is said to be a shrine established by Yamatohime-no-Mikoto when she moored her boat during her journey up the Tokida River (Outer Tokida River).<ref name="ic"/> She stopped here because the river narrowed and boats could no longer pass.<ref name="tc5"/>

In the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, it is recorded as “Ōkami no Mifune Shrine.”<ref name="sk8"/> “Ōkami no Mifune” is thought to mean the boat upon which {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qid=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}} rode. Sonoda Moriyoshi suggested that after the transfer of the deity, the boat container (*mifunashiro*) holding the sacred casket (*mihishiro*) that enshrined the {{ill|lt=divine body|Q327532|qid=Q327532|1=Shintai}} of Amaterasu Ōmikami may have been placed at Mifune Shrine.<ref name="sk8"/>

The enshrined deity is Ōkami no Mikagekawa no Kami.<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk">Gakken Publishing (2013): p. 68</ref> This deity is regarded either as the {{ill|lt=guardian deity|Q131278957|qid=Q131278957|1=Guardian deities}} of the Tokida River, which irrigates the surrounding fields,<ref name="ic"/> or as a guardian deity of waterborne transportation.<ref name="gk"/> The same {{ill|lt=kami (Shinto)|Q524158|qid=Q524158|lt=deity|1=Kami}} is also enshrined at {{ill|lt=Kano Shrine|Q17225745|qid=Q17225745|1=Kano Shrine}}, another subsidiary shrine of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Kaneko (1983): p. 59</ref> The term “Mikage” carries meanings of {{ill|lt=spirit|Q9165|qid=Q9165|1=Soul}} and blessing (“okage”), and according to *Jingū Tenryaku*, it refers to the spirit of a great deity enshrined by the river that supplies water to the {{ill|lt=sacred fields|Q10855080|qid=Q10855080|1=Shinden (divine field)}}.<ref name="sk9">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p. 379</ref>

There are alternative theories regarding the enshrined deity: *Ise Nisho Daijingū Shinmei Hisho* records it as “Ōkami no Mifune no Kami,” *Engishiki Jinmyōchō Hian-shū* as “Ame-no-Torifune no Kami,” and *Ise no Kuni Jinmyōchō Kōshō* as “Toriishikusufune no Kami.”<ref name="sk0"/>

=== Mumino Shrine ===
Mumino Shrine ranks 15th among the 16 auxiliary shrines of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Hall, ed. (1929): pp. 13–14</ref> Its shrine building was discontinued, and it is now enshrined together with Mifune Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Hall, ed. (1929): p. 14</ref>

The enshrined deities are Samukawahiko no Mikoto and Samukawahime no Mikoto.<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/> They are guardian deities of the Tokida River<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/> and are said to be children of Ōminakami no Mikoto.<ref name="gk"/> “Samukawa,” the name of the deities, is an alternate name for the Tokida River, and is said to have been given by Yamatohime-no-Mikoto because the river’s water was cold.<ref name="tc5"/>

=== History ===
By definition, as a subsidiary shrine of Ise Grand Shrine, Mifune Shrine must have been founded before the compilation of the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, that is, before {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}).<ref name="ic2">Ise Bunkasha (2008): p. 22</ref> The *Kōtaijingū Gishikichō* records the phrase “designated and celebrated by Princess Yamatohime.”<ref name="sk8"/> Since it appears in this text, the shrine is considered to have existed before {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} 23 ({{ill|lt=804|Q29998|qid=Q29998|1=804}}).<ref name="ic2"/>

In {{ill|lt=ancient times|Q41493|qid=Q41493|1=Ancient history}}, Toba belonged to Tanabe-go of {{ill|lt=Watarai District|Q1131032|qid=Q1131032|1=Watarai District}}, but in {{ill|lt=Taika|Q1077930|qid=Q1077930|1=Taika (era)}} 5 ({{ill|lt=649|Q31117|qid=Q31117|1=649}}), Taki District was separated from Watarai District, and the area came to belong to Ari-go of Taki District.<ref name="tc5"/> Because of this history, the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō* lists “Ōkami no Mifune Shrine” under Watarai District.<ref name="sk9"/>

From the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|qid=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}} onward, rituals were discontinued, but on {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 3, {{ill|lt=8th month 29th day (lunar calendar)|Q840048|qid=Q840048|1=August 29 (Lunisolar)}} ({{ill|lt=Gregorian calendar|Q12138|qid=Q12138|1=Gregorian calendar}}: {{ill|lt=1663|Q7577|qid=Q7577|1=1663}} {{ill|lt=September 30|Q2881|qid=Q2881|1=September 30}}), the shrine was reestablished at its present site.<ref name="sk8"/> At that time, remains of moats, old post holes, and decayed wood were discovered, leading the site to be regarded as the former shrine location.<ref>Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): pp. 378–379</ref> {{ill|lt=Mikanagi Kiyonao|Q6537624|qid=Q6537624|1=Mikannagi Kiyonao}} supported this identification, while Nakagawa Tsunemasa argued that the former site was a local {{ill|lt=ujigami|Q767655|qid=Q767655|1=Ujigami}} shrine in a neighboring village, colloquially called “Mifune-sha.”<ref name="sk9"/> In {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|qid=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} 14 ({{ill|lt=1843|Q7629|qid=Q7629|1=1843}}), a stone lantern was installed at the shrine entrance.<ref name="gk"/>

In {{ill|lt=Meiji 4|Q11512280|qid=Q11512280|1=Meiji – year 4}} ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|qid=Q7746|1=1871}}), Mumino Shrine, whose location had been unknown since the medieval period, was enshrined together with Mifune Shrine.<ref name="sk0"/>

=== Access ===
;Public transportation
* About a 17-minute walk (approximately 900 m) from {{ill|lt=Tokida Station|Q7813584|qid=Q7813584|1=Tokida Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Sangū Line|Q872023|qid=Q872023|1=Sangū Line}} of {{ill|lt=JR Central|Q513679|qid=Q513679|1=Central Japan Railway Company}}.<ref name="ic-P63">Ise Bunkasha, ed. (2008): p. 63</ref> Walk along the {{ill|lt=Miyagawa irrigation canal|Q11454721|qid=Q11454721|1=Miyagawa irrigation canal}} from the south side of Tokida Station; the elevated ground on the right is Mifune Shrine / Mumino Shrine.<ref name="ic"/>
;By car
* About 14 minutes (approximately 5.9 {{ill|lt=kilometers|Q828224|qid=Q828224|lt=km|1=Kilometre}}) from {{ill|lt=Tamaki Interchange|Q11572465|qid=Q11572465|lt=Tamaki IC|1=Tamaki interchange}} on the {{ill|lt=Ise Expressway|Q6079578|qid=Q6079578|1=Ise Expressway}}. There is no {{ill|lt=parking lot|Q6501349|qid=Q6501349|1=Parking lot}} nearby.

