'''Mifune Shrine''' (みふねじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Sessha|Q1071160|qid=Q1071160|lt=subsidiary shrine|1=Setsumatsusha}} of the {{ill|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|Q687168|qid=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} {{ill|lt=Kōtaijingū|Q11581011|qid=Q11581011|1=Kōtai Jingū}} (Inner Shrine). This article also describes '''Mumino Shrine''' (むみのじんじゃ), which is enshrined at the same site as Mifune Shrine.

Both are shrines that enshrine {{ill|lt=water deities|Q3137449|qid=Q3137449|lt=river gods|1=Suijin}}.<ref name="ic">Ise Bunka-sha, ed. (2008): p.64</ref>

=== Overview ===
This section describes matters common to both shrines.

They are located in Toba (read as Toba or Doba), {{ill|lt=Taki Town|Q1203963|qid=Q1203963|1=Taki, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Taki District|Q1042360|qid=Q1042360|1=Taki District, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Mie Prefecture|Q128196|qid=Q128196|1=Mie Prefecture}}.<ref name="sk8">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p.378</ref> The place name “Toba” means “stopping place,” and is said to derive from the fact that the boat of {{ill|lt=Yamatohime-no-mikoto|Q4388732|qid=Q4388732|1=Yamatohime-no-mikoto}} stopped there.<ref name="tc5">Kaneko (1983): p.55</ref>

The {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine buildings|1=UNKNOWN}} are constructed in the {{ill|lt=Shinmei-zukuri|Q930545|qid=Q930545|1=Shinmei-zukuri}} style and are surrounded by a {{ill|lt=tamagaki|Q3078312|qid=Q3078312|1=Sacred fences}} fence. No {{ill|lt=offertory box|Q988479|qid=Q988479|1=Saisen}} is placed. At the entrance to the shrine grounds stands a {{ill|lt=stone lantern|Q762277|qid=Q762277|1=Nightlight}}.<ref name="ic"/> The area of the shrine grounds is 975 {{ill|lt=tsubo|Q706688|qid=Q706688|1=Pyeong}} (approximately 3,223 {{ill|lt=square meters|Q25343|qid=Q25343|lt=m<sup>2</sup>|1=Square metre}}).<ref name="sk0">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p.380</ref>

=== Mifune Shrine ===
Mifune Shrine ranks 24th among the 27 subsidiary shrines of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Office, ed. (1929): pp.9–11</ref> It is a shrine established at a place where Yamatohime-no-mikoto moored her boat during her journey upstream along the Tokida River.<ref name="ic"/> She stopped here because the river became too narrow for boats to pass.<ref name="tc5"/>

In the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, it is recorded as “Ōkami no Mifune Shrine.”<ref name="sk8"/> “Ōkami no Mifune” is thought to mean the boat on which {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qid=Q455602|1=Amaterasu}} rides, and Sonoda Moriyoshi conjectured that the vessel (mifunashiro) containing the sacred container for the {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|qid=Q327532|1=Shintai}} of Amaterasu Ōmikami was placed at Mifune Shrine after the transfer of the deity.<ref name="sk8"/>

The enshrined deity is Ōkami no Mikagekawa no Kami.<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk">Gakken Publishing (2013): p.68</ref> This deity is regarded as the {{ill|lt=guardian deity|Q131278957|qid=Q131278957|1=Guardian deities}} of the Tokida River, which irrigates fields,<ref name="ic"/> or as a guardian deity of water transportation.<ref name="gk"/> The same {{ill|lt=kami (Shinto)|Q524158|qid=Q524158|lt=deity|1=Kami}} is also enshrined at {{ill|lt=Kano Shrine|Q17225745|qid=Q17225745|1=Kano Shrine}}, another subsidiary shrine of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Kaneko (1983): p.59</ref> “Mikage” carries meanings of {{ill|lt=spirit|Q9165|qid=Q9165|1=Soul}} and blessing (“okage”), and *Jingū Tenryaku* explains it as the spirit of the great deity enshrined beside the river that draws water to the {{ill|lt=sacred rice fields|Q10855080|qid=Q10855080|1=Shinden (divine field)}}.<ref name="sk9">Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): p.379</ref>

There are alternative theories regarding the enshrined deity: *Ise Nishō Daijingū Shinmei Hisho* gives “Ōkami no Mifune no Kami,” *Engishiki Jinmyōchō Hian-shū* gives “Ame no Torifune no Kami,” and *Ise no Kuni Jinmyōchō Kōshō* gives “Toriishi Kusufune no Kami.”<ref name="sk0"/>

=== Mumino Shrine ===
Mumino Shrine ranks 15th among the 16 auxiliary shrines of the Inner Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Office, ed. (1929): pp.13–14</ref> Its shrine building was discontinued, and it is enshrined together with Mifune Shrine.<ref>Ujiyamada City Office, ed. (1929): p.14</ref>

The enshrined deities are Samukawahiko no Mikoto and Samukawahime no Mikoto.<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/> They are guardian deities of the Tokida River<ref name="ic"/><ref name="gk"/> and children of Ōminakami no Mikoto.<ref name="gk"/> “Samukawa,” the name of the deities, is an alternate name for the Tokida River, said to have been given by Yamatohime-no-mikoto because the river water was cold.<ref name="tc5"/>

=== History ===
By definition as a subsidiary shrine of Ise Grand Shrine, Mifune Shrine must have been founded before the compilation of the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, that is, before the 5th year of {{ill|lt=Enchō (era)|Q1327274|qid=Q1327274|lt=Enchō|1=Enchō}} ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|qid=Q30470|1=927}}).<ref name="ic2">Ise Bunka-sha (2008): p.22</ref> The *Kōtaijingū Gishikichō* records “Yamatohime Naishinnō Sadame-iwai.”<ref name="sk8"/> Since it is mentioned in the *Kōtaijingū Gishikichō*, it is considered to have existed before the 23rd year of {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|qid=Q1373176|1=Enryaku}} ({{ill|lt=804|Q29998|qid=Q29998|1=804}}).<ref name="ic2"/>

In {{ill|lt=ancient times|Q41493|qid=Q41493|1=Ancient history}}, Toba belonged to Tanabe-go of {{ill|lt=Watarai District|Q1131032|qid=Q1131032|1=Watarai District}}, but in the 5th year of {{ill|lt=Taika|Q1077930|qid=Q1077930|1=Taika (era)}} ({{ill|lt=649|Q31117|qid=Q31117|1=649}}), Taki District was separated from Watarai District, and the area came to belong to Uni-go of Taki District.<ref name="tc5"/> Because of this history, the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō* lists “Ōkami no Mifune Shrine” under Watarai District.<ref name="sk9"/>

From the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|qid=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}} onward, rituals ceased, but the shrine was revived at its present location on the 29th day of the 8th month of the 3rd year of {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} ({{ill|lt=Gregorian calendar|Q12138|qid=Q12138|1=Gregorian calendar}}: September 30, {{ill|lt=1663|Q7577|qid=Q7577|1=1663}}).<ref name="sk8"/> At that time, traces of a {{ill|lt=moat|Q88480|qid=Q88480|1=Moat}}, old post holes, and decayed wood were discovered, leading the site to be considered the former shrine location.<ref>Shikinaisha Research Association, ed. (1990): pp.378–379</ref> {{ill|lt=Mikanagi Kiyonao|Q6537624|qid=Q6537624|1=Mikannagi Kiyonao}} supported this theory, while Nakagawa Tsunemasa argued that a {{ill|lt=ujigami|Q767655|qid=Q767655|1=Ujigami}} shrine in a neighboring village, colloquially called “Mifune-sha” by locals, was the former site.<ref name="sk9"/> In the 14th year of {{ill|lt=Tenpō|Q1369045|qid=Q1369045|1=Tenpō}} ({{ill|lt=1843|Q7629|qid=Q7629|1=1843}}), a stone lantern was installed at the shrine entrance.<ref name="gk"/>

In {{ill|lt=Meiji 4|Q11512280|qid=Q11512280|1=Meiji – year 4}} ({{ill|lt=1871|Q7746|qid=Q7746|1=1871}}), Mumino Shrine, whose location had been unknown since the medieval period, was enshrined together with Mifune Shrine.<ref name="sk0"/>

=== Access ===
;Public transportation
* About a 17-minute walk (approximately 900 m) from {{ill|lt=Tokida Station|Q7813584|qid=Q7813584|1=Tokida Station}} on the {{ill|lt=JR|Q513679|qid=Q513679|1=Central Japan Railway Company}} {{ill|lt=Sangū Line|Q872023|qid=Q872023|1=Sangū Line}}.<ref name="ic-P63">Ise Bunka-sha, ed. (2008): p.63</ref> Walk along the {{ill|lt=Miyagawa Irrigation Canal|Q11454721|qid=Q11454721|1=Miyagawa Irrigation Canal}} from the front (south) side of Tokida Station; the elevated ground visible on the right is Mifune Shrine / Mumino Shrine.<ref name="ic"/>
;By car
* About 14 minutes (approximately 5.9 {{ill|lt=kilometers|Q828224|qid=Q828224|lt=km|1=Kilometre}}) from {{ill|lt=Tamaki Interchange|Q11572465|qid=Q11572465|lt=Tamaki IC|1=Tamaki interchange}} on the {{ill|lt=Ise Expressway|Q6079578|qid=Q6079578|1=Ise Expressway}}. There is no {{ill|lt=parking lot|Q6501349|qid=Q6501349|1=Parking lot}} nearby.

